# Agent Rules for Service Repositories

## Shared Architecture

This service follows the shared arch method from the central architecture
repository.

Install or update the local method surface with `agent-arch-install`. The
solution repository should rely only on the files installed by the approved
`solution-standard` profile, not on a manual copy of arbitrary files from the
central repository.

This file is the shared instruction entry point for Codex, GitHub Copilot, and
other agents that support `AGENTS.md`. If `CLAUDE.md` exists, it should defer
to this file for all repository-wide policy and workflow rules.

Before architecture-sensitive implementation or review:

- Use `arch-intake` when the repository must first be understood, aligned, or compared against central architecture.
- Use `arch-consume` to resolve architecture context and impact.
- Read central architecture with `arch-read` before changing shared contracts,
  APIs, FHIR models, or security-sensitive behavior.
- Use `arch-escalate` if the needed change belongs in normative architecture
  rather than this repository.
- Use `arch-systematic-debugging` for bugs, failing tests, integration issues,
  or unexpected behavior before proposing fixes.

If this repository installs the optional creativity-first pilot surface:

- Use `arch-context` for insight work, alternative analysis, and local
  innovation before converging on a solution.
- You may choose a local path that differs from current normative architecture,
  but only when the choice is deliberate, analyzed against the central
  architecture, and captured in the local deviation record.
- Feed reusable improvements back through `arch-escalate` instead of keeping a
  justified local deviation hidden.

## Superpowers-Style Workflow

If the team wants Superpowers-style process support in GitHub Copilot:

- Prefer arch-compatible local skills and instructions over importing upstream
  Superpowers behavior unchanged.
- Treat upstream Superpowers as a source of workflow patterns, not as the
  authority for policy or file locations.
- Do not assume mandatory worktrees, mandatory TDD, or `docs/superpowers/`
  paths unless the team explicitly chooses that.

## Tooling

```sh
export ARCH_DIR="${ARCH_DIR:-${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/agent-arch}"
. .github/agent-arch/source.env
if [ ! -d "$ARCH_DIR/.git" ]; then
  git clone --depth 1 "https://github.com/$AGENT_ARCH_SOURCE_REPO.git" "$ARCH_DIR"
else
    git -C "$ARCH_DIR" pull --ff-only
fi
export PATH="$PATH:$PWD/scripts"
```

Install or update the approved local method surface with:

```sh
npx skills add <owner>/agent-arch --skill agent-arch-install -a github-copilot -y --copy
sh .agents/skills/agent-arch-install/install-method.sh --repo <owner>/agent-arch --profile solution-standard
```

Fallback when `npx skills` is unavailable:

```sh
mkdir -p scripts
curl -fsSL "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/<owner>/agent-arch/main/scripts/agent-arch-install.sh" -o scripts/agent-arch-install.sh
sh scripts/agent-arch-install.sh --repo <owner>/agent-arch --profile solution-standard
```

Bootstrap behavior:

- installs `AGENTS.md` as the shared instruction file for most agents
- installs a thin `CLAUDE.md` adapter for Claude-specific additions
- does not overwrite an existing `AGENTS.md` or `CLAUDE.md` unless you install
  with `--force`
- continues to update the rest of the managed method surface normally

## Arch Knowledge

If the repository enables local architecture knowledge support, use:

- `arch-knowledge flush`
- `arch-knowledge compile`
- `arch-knowledge lint`

`flush` and `compile` use the configured LLM adapter command. `lint` is
deterministic.

If the creativity-first pilot surface is installed, keep deliberate local
deviations under `docs/arch-knowledge/deviations/` so the baseline, the local
choice, and the proposal back to central architecture stay traceable.

## Escalation Rules

- Local implementation stays local when it does not change normative architecture.
- Alternatives, chosen solutions, and guardrails can be captured in solution-space records when the repo needs reusable solution context.
- Cross-repo dependencies should be made visible in the target repository with a
  dedicated issue.
- Missing or unclear central architecture should be escalated through
  `arch-escalate`.
